Emacs Lisp is the extension language for the GNU Emacs text editor, and in fact, most of the functionality of Emacs is implemented using Emacs Lisp. Users generally customize Emacs' behavior by adding Emacs Lisp statements to their .emacs, or writing separate packages. A guide to learning Emacs Lisp for non-programmers can be found here.

Emacs Lisp differs from most other lisps in two main ways:

  1. It has special features for scanning and parsing text, as well as features for handling files, buffers, arrays, displays, and subprocesses. This is due to the fact that it is designed to be used in a text editor
  2. It uses dynamic scope as opposed to lexical scope. This was done very intentionally, the reasons are well explained in the 1981 paper on Emacs.

This tag is for questions about migrating existing applications, or legacy code, from Visual Basic 6 to a more modern platform. Unfortunately migration is usually a tricky task. The most common target platforms are VB.Net and C#.

Here are some typical motives for migration

  • To use a more modern programming language for enhancements.
    • This will give some increase in productivity.
    • This also keeps the developers happy, which is a valid business benefit in itself. There are bigger gains in productivity from attracting and retaining good developers than anything else.
  • To use a fully supported programming stack.
    • Although the VB6 runtime is still fully supported by Microsoft as part of Windows, many people worry that support will be dropped one day. The VB6 IDE is no longer supported.

Frequently asked questions

  • What is the best strategy for migration? There are a range of different opinions, as can be seen from the questions tagged vb-migration! For what it's worth, here is a Microsoft UK page with their advice.
  • Should we select VB.Net or C#?
  • What are the risks around continuing to rely on VB6 applications?
  • Will VB6 live forever like COBOL?

In LINQ to SQL, the data model of a relational database is mapped to an object model expressed in the programming language of the developer. When the application runs, LINQ to SQL translates into SQL the language-integrated queries (LINQ) in the object model and sends them to the database for execution. When the database returns the results, LINQ to SQL translates them back to objects that you can work with in your own programming language.

The Spring Framework supports integration with Hibernate, Java Persistence API (JPA), Java Data Objects (JDO) and iBATIS SQL Maps for resource management, data access object (DAO) implementations, and transaction strategies. For example, for Hibernate there is first-class support with several convenient IoC features that address many typical Hibernate integration issues. You can configure all of the supported features for O/R (object relational) mapping tools through Dependency Injection. They can participate in Spring's resource and transaction management, and they comply with Spring's generic transaction and DAO exception hierarchies. The recommended integration style is to code DAOs against plain Hibernate, JPA, and JDO APIs. The older style of using Spring's DAO templates is no longer recommended; however, coverage of this style can be found in the Section A.1, “Classic ORM usage” in the appendices.

Spring adds significant enhancements to the ORM layer of your choice when you create data access applications. You can leverage as much of the integration support as you wish, and you should compare this integration effort with the cost and risk of building a similar infrastructure in-house. You can use much of the ORM support as you would a library, regardless of technology, because everything is designed as a set of reusable JavaBeans. ORM in a Spring IoC container facilitates configuration and deployment. Thus most examples in this section show configuration inside a Spring container.

Source:

Spring Reference: Object Relational Mapping (ORM) Data Access
Questions relating to Spring's ORM framework which contains support for Hibernate, JPA, JDO and iBATIS

In computer science, a doubly-linked list is a linked data structure that consists of a set of sequentially-linked records called nodes. Each node contains two fields, called links, that are references to the previous and to the next node in the sequence of nodes.

.NET Micro Framework

The .NET Micro Framework is .NET for small and resource constrained devices. It offers a complete and innovative development and execution environment that brings the productivity of modern computing tools to this class of devices.

For current .NET developers, this means that they can now create applications that run on a range of devices from targeted devices like remote controls to PCs and Servers and on to the cloud – all with the same programming model and tools.

For current Embedded developers, this means that they can now leverage the productivity gains that have been achieved on the desktop and reduce their time to market.

The .NET Micro Framework is a fully integrated Visual Studio experience brings a reliable and productive development system to the embedded world.

The ASP.NET MVC Framework is a Microsoft web application framework that implements the model-view-controller (MVC) pattern. Based on ASP.NET, it allows software developers to build a Web application as a composition of three roles: Model, View and Controller.

A model represents the state of a particular aspect of the application. Frequently, a model maps to a database table with the entries in the table representing the state of the application. A controller handles interactions and updates the model to reflect a change in state of the application, and then passes information to the view. A view accepts necessary information from the controller and renders a user interface to display that.

The latest stable version is available from the Microsoft Download Center website.

Latest announcements from Microsoft usually come from Scott Guthrie's blog. Other notable blogs relating to MVC include Phil Haack and Scott Hanselman.

A framework for building scalable, standards-based web applications using well-established design patterns and the power of ASP.NET and the .NET Framework. This tag is used for problems specific to version 3 of the framework.

Zend Technologies Ltd.

Zend Technologies is a software company offering a number of (free and commercial) PHP related technologies, including Zend Framework, Zend Server and Zend Studio. They sponsor a number of other projects and organize ZendCon, one of the largest PHP conferences in the world. Zend also offers trainings and certification programs.

Tag Purpose

The zend tag is an umbrella tag and should be avoided. Because Zend is a company offering a broad choice of products and services, there is no clear definition of when this tag makes sense to use. In general, you should try to use one of the more distinct tags, like

  • zend-framework or zf for questions about Zend Framework,
  • zend-studio for questions about Zend's commercial IDE,
  • zend-server for questions about Zend's server appliance,
  • zend-guard for questions about Zend's source code obfuscator,
  • zend-engine for questions about writing extensions and the inner workings of PHP.

There are a lot of things called "PDB" which are potentially on-topic here; sometimes the asker won't know which one they're dealing with.

The easiest to distinguish is probably the Python debugger named pdb, because it doesn't involve the file extension .pdb; its tag is pdb-python.

Formats stored in files with a .pdb extension:

  • The Program Database debugging information format(s) used by MS development tools; see the tag pdb-ms.
  • The "Protein Data Bank" format, designed for representing experimentally-determined molecular structures for proteins (though not restricted to that use, as evidenced by the abundance of water molecules in the protein structure files), as determined by (for example) x-ray crystallography. See the slightly misnamed tag protein-database.

About Rails

Rails is a framework built on Ruby that provides developers and easy way to build an full-featured application. It is popular among many developers from novices to experiences developers working for large corporations. In short, it utilizes MVC fundamentals and lives by the phrase 'convention over configuration' (CoC) and 'don't repeat yourself' (DRY).

Rails 3

Rails 3 is the most recent version of the Rails framework and provides a few upgrades and differences from its predecessors:

  • Brand new router with an emphasis on RESTful declarations
  • New Action Mailer API modeled after Action Controller
  • New Active Record chainable query language built on top of relational algebra
  • Unobtrusive JavaScript helpers with drivers for Prototype and jQuery
  • Explicit dependency management with Bundler

These are cited from the Rails 3 release notes. Some other new features include a better console environment. You can now start the rails server, console, etc using the alias rails:

rails s          #starts rails server
rails server     #starts rails server
rails c          #starts rails console
rails console    #starts rails console

For more information on changes, see the [Rails 3 release notes].2

Caveats

This is such a huge topic that it's actually worth mentioning in this wiki. All too often, Rails is compared to another popular web-founded programming language - PHP. Despite what you may hear, there is no competition between PHP and Rails.

Furthermore, PHP is often directly compared to Rails in terms of efficiency, usability, scalability, etc. This is an entirely unfair comparison. Rails (actually Ruby on Rails) is a framework built on Ruby. If you read an article comparing Rails and PHP, the article is unfounded.

To adequately compare the two languages, one must either:

  • compare PHP and Ruby
  • compare Rails and a PHP framework like CodeIgniter or CakePHP

Please keep this is mind in literature you come across in your development.

Helpful Links

  • The official RoR guides
  • Rails 3 specific Railscasts by Ryan Bates
  • Rails 3 Git Log/Bugs
  • Rails 3 release notes
Ruby on Rails 3 is the most recent version of a quickly-growing, rapid application development framework based on Ruby and meta programming techniques.

Html Agility Pack (a.k.a "HAP") is an agile HTML parser that builds a read/write DOM and supports plain XPATH or XSLT (you actually don't HAVE to understand XPATH nor XSLT to use it, don't worry...). It is a .NET code library that allows you to parse "out of the web" HTML files. The parser is very tolerant with "real world" malformed HTML. The object model is very similar to what proposes System.Xml, but for HTML documents (or streams).

Html Agility Pack now supports Linq to Objects (via a LINQ to Xml Like interface).

Sample applications:

  • Page fixing or generation. You can fix a page the way you want, modify the DOM, add nodes, copy nodes, well... you name it.
  • Web scanners. You can easily get to img/src or a/hrefs with a bunch XPATH queries.
  • Web scrapers. You can easily scrap any existing web page into an RSS feed for example, with just an XSLT file serving as the binding. Examples are is provided.

There is no dependency on anything else than .Net's XPATH implementation. There is no dependency on Internet Explorer's MSHTML dll or W3C's HTML tidy or ActiveX / COM object, or anything like that. There is also no adherence to XHTML or XML, although you can actually produce XML using the tool.

The binaries and source code can be downloaded from CodePlex here: http://htmlagilitypack.codeplex.com/
Html Agility Pack is an HTML parser for the .NET platform. It is very tolerant to "real world" malformed HTML.

The term "capture" has many different meanings in programming, among them:

  • Audio and video capture, also screen capture
  • A regular expression can "capture" part of the match and then refer to it with a backreference during string replacement. Most regex libraries also provide API-level access to capture results.
  • When a lexical scope is created by referring to names in the enclosing scope from a nested function (e.g. anonymous function or anonymous method) or lambda expression, the variables thus referred to are "captured".
  • Javascript event handling has a "capturing" phase which allows the programmer to prevent bubbling of certain events.

"capturing" is ambiguous.  Please specify whether you mean capturing audio/video (tag `audio-capture` or `video-capture` or `screen-scraping`), regular expression captures (tag: `capturing-group`), or creation of a lexical scope (captured variables) in a lambda expression or nested function, or the capture phase of event handling in JavaScript (tag: `event-handling` or `javascript-events`)
